WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:03.211
[♪♪♪]

00:15.599 --> 00:16.851
[SIGHS]

00:18.560 --> 00:20.604
Julie!

00:22.230 --> 00:24.274
That's really good.

00:24.274 --> 00:25.943
Thank you.

00:25.943 --> 00:30.030
I mean, I always knew
you loved art, but lately,

00:30.030 --> 00:31.573
you seem downright inspired.

00:31.573 --> 00:33.993
I think it's being
around the children.

00:33.993 --> 00:37.913
Something about the openness
of their minds, it's very...

00:37.913 --> 00:39.581
freeing.

00:39.581 --> 00:41.959
They make it easy
to feel creative.

00:41.959 --> 00:43.961
You're doing really well.

00:43.961 --> 00:46.296
Don't sound so surprised.

00:46.296 --> 00:48.131
I'm not surprised at all.

00:54.596 --> 00:56.891
Care to do the honors,
Miss Thatcher?

00:59.226 --> 01:01.144
[GIGGLES]

01:01.144 --> 01:04.147
Why, thank you,
Miss Thatcher.

01:05.566 --> 01:07.902
[COWBELL CLANGING]

01:07.902 --> 01:09.486
JULIE:
Come along, everyone,

01:09.486 --> 01:11.947
and bring those beautiful minds
with you!

01:11.947 --> 01:13.991
Good morning. Hi.

01:13.991 --> 01:16.827
[LAUGHS]

01:18.245 --> 01:20.998
You could cut the budget
for new bunks in the jail.

01:20.998 --> 01:23.542
Those mattresses
are so old and thin.

01:23.542 --> 01:26.169
It's the jail,
not the Ritz!

01:28.505 --> 01:30.215
Can I help you?

01:30.215 --> 01:32.133
You can,
if you're Mayor Stanton.

01:32.133 --> 01:33.134
I am.

01:33.134 --> 01:34.511
I'm Jacob Weston,

01:34.511 --> 01:36.638
with the National
Pacific Railroad.

01:36.638 --> 01:38.724
It's nice to meet you.
We've been waiting.

01:38.724 --> 01:40.225
This is our Sheriff,
Bill Avery.

01:40.225 --> 01:43.062
Of course. Bill Avery.
Heard a lot about you.

01:43.062 --> 01:44.939
Hope I get a chance
to defend myself.

01:44.939 --> 01:46.481
[LAUGHS]
No need.

01:46.481 --> 01:48.067
Everything said
was positive.

01:48.067 --> 01:49.818
So, you're here to talk
about our new depot?

01:49.818 --> 01:51.028
I am, indeed.

01:51.028 --> 01:52.863
Great. Now the line's
been completed,

01:52.863 --> 01:54.990
we'd like to see it open
as soon as possible.

01:54.990 --> 01:57.158
The town's been
waiting a long time.

01:57.158 --> 01:59.661
Yes, well...

01:59.661 --> 02:02.039
I'm sorry to say
they're gonna be disappointed.

02:02.039 --> 02:04.165
What do you mean?
I mean...

02:04.165 --> 02:07.377
we've decided not to build
a depot in Hope Valley.

02:07.377 --> 02:09.088
You can't do that.

02:10.255 --> 02:13.341
We can, and we did.

02:18.305 --> 02:20.515
[♪♪♪]

02:39.159 --> 02:42.245
Mr. Weston, why aren't you
building a depot here?

02:42.245 --> 02:45.040
There are greater cost benefits
to build in Jameson.

02:45.040 --> 02:46.416
But we have
a contract.

02:46.416 --> 02:47.709
And we have lawyers.

02:47.709 --> 02:49.962
Look, this was
a business decision.

02:49.962 --> 02:52.213
It wasn't personal.
You're wrong.

02:52.213 --> 02:54.466
It's personal to everyone
in this town.

02:54.466 --> 02:56.010
A lot of people didn't even

02:56.010 --> 02:58.595
want your company to lay track
through our valley,

02:58.595 --> 02:59.805
but once it was voted on,

02:59.805 --> 03:01.723
everyone worked
to welcome the railroad.

03:01.723 --> 03:03.600
It's a betrayal
of all of their trust.

03:03.600 --> 03:06.020
It wasn't my decision.
I'm just the messenger.

03:06.020 --> 03:07.646
I like the way
the Greeks dealt

03:07.646 --> 03:09.272
with people
who brought bad news.

03:09.272 --> 03:11.566
They say this town
has an honorable sheriff.

03:11.566 --> 03:14.193
Well, you might've
heard wrong about that.

03:15.362 --> 03:17.156
Mr. Weston...

03:17.156 --> 03:20.325
let's go somewhere where we
can talk. I own the cafe.

03:20.325 --> 03:22.494
it's quiet this time of day.

03:22.494 --> 03:24.997
We'd just be wasting
our breath, Mrs. Stanton.

03:24.997 --> 03:26.874
The decision's been made.

03:26.874 --> 03:29.960
Now, if you'll excuse me,
I have an office to clear out.

03:32.629 --> 03:34.506
I can't believe
this is happening.

03:34.506 --> 03:36.550
He's got an army of lawyers
on his side.

03:36.550 --> 03:39.011
We've got to persuade him
without going to court.

03:39.011 --> 03:41.596
How are we gonna do that?
I don't know, but I need you

03:41.596 --> 03:43.765
to keep him from
leaving this town.

03:43.765 --> 03:45.893
[♪♪♪]

03:45.893 --> 03:48.187
I can do that.

03:49.855 --> 03:51.523
For our art class today,

03:51.523 --> 03:54.484
I'm going to show you
the secret to the perfect face.

03:54.484 --> 03:58.238
First, you draw an oval,
then...

03:58.238 --> 04:00.949
divide it into quarters.

04:00.949 --> 04:03.577
Divide the lower half again...

04:03.577 --> 04:05.996
the nose goes here,

04:05.996 --> 04:08.832
the mouth, here,

04:08.832 --> 04:12.627
and the eyes... go here.

04:13.921 --> 04:15.005
Miss Thatcher,

04:15.005 --> 04:18.299
is it a girl
or a boy's face?

04:18.299 --> 04:20.552
It can be whichever
you want it to be, Anna.

04:20.552 --> 04:21.511
You choose.

04:21.511 --> 04:24.681
And then
you add eyebrows,

04:24.681 --> 04:26.100
and ears...

04:26.100 --> 04:28.309
[♪♪♪]

04:31.312 --> 04:34.149
Oh! Dottie! I love
this new space we have.

04:34.149 --> 04:36.317
The bank having to relocate
is the best thing

04:36.317 --> 04:39.071
that could've happened!
How are the new designs coming?

04:39.071 --> 04:40.739
Great!
You're going to love them.

04:40.739 --> 04:43.533
These sketches would impress
Madame Chéruit herself.

04:43.533 --> 04:46.245
Good, because I have news.

04:46.245 --> 04:47.788
I received a telegram

04:47.788 --> 04:49.748
from a high-end boutique
in Union City.

04:49.748 --> 04:52.626
They heard about the gowns
we're selling Cape Fullerton.

04:52.626 --> 04:53.710
And?

04:53.710 --> 04:55.378
They'd like
to place an order!

04:55.378 --> 04:59.174
Oh, ho, ho! Oh, Dottie!
Congratulations!

04:59.174 --> 05:00.592
That's wonderful!

05:00.592 --> 05:02.385
I couldn't have done it
without your designs.

05:02.385 --> 05:04.387
Oh, I can see it now--
Union City,

05:04.387 --> 05:06.265
Hamilton,
then New York,

05:06.265 --> 05:09.059
and someday...
Paris.

05:09.059 --> 05:10.435
Oh!

05:10.435 --> 05:12.187
One step at a time.

05:12.187 --> 05:14.522
I'm off to Buxton
to buy fabric.

05:14.522 --> 05:16.733
Clara's busy finishing
a dress in the back.

05:16.733 --> 05:18.152
The shop is yours.

05:18.152 --> 05:21.696
Oh. And good luck
with the sketches, Madame.

05:24.074 --> 05:26.076
Ladies. I'm off to Buxton.

05:26.076 --> 05:27.953
Oh! Have a good trip.
Thank you.

05:27.953 --> 05:29.621
Well.

05:29.621 --> 05:32.040
Oh!

05:34.960 --> 05:37.587
Good afternoon, ladies.
Can I help you with anything?

05:37.587 --> 05:39.881
Oh, we were just
admiring this dress.

05:39.881 --> 05:42.050
Oh, well,
you have good taste.

05:42.050 --> 05:44.678
That's one of
my original designs. Elegant,

05:44.678 --> 05:46.847
yet subtle...
wouldn't you agree?

05:46.847 --> 05:48.598
You're so talented!

05:48.598 --> 05:51.018
I've never seen
such a stunning dress.

05:51.018 --> 05:52.727
Would you care
to try it on, Wilma?

05:52.727 --> 05:54.646
I can't.
Oh, why not?

05:54.646 --> 05:56.064
You said
you needed a dress.

05:56.064 --> 05:57.607
It would look
beautiful on you.

05:57.607 --> 05:59.109
It truly would.
Your eyes

05:59.109 --> 06:00.443
and that color?

06:00.443 --> 06:02.196
I'd love to,
but it looks expensive.

06:02.196 --> 06:04.781
We should be going.
Thank you for your time.

06:04.781 --> 06:07.242
Sorry to bother you.
Oh! No. Not at all.

06:07.242 --> 06:09.744
If you change your mind,
you know where to find me.

06:09.744 --> 06:12.580
Are you sure?
Yes. I really can't.

06:12.580 --> 06:15.416
JULIE [GASPS]:
Nicely done, Laura!

06:15.416 --> 06:17.002
LAURA:
Thanks, Miss Thatcher.

06:19.462 --> 06:20.797
Anna...

06:20.797 --> 06:22.507
since you're
drawing a girl,

06:22.507 --> 06:25.177
try to make the lips
a little fuller.

06:27.054 --> 06:28.471
Like this?

06:28.471 --> 06:30.349
That's it! Good.

06:31.683 --> 06:33.352
Can I see?

06:33.352 --> 06:34.686
In a minute.

06:34.686 --> 06:35.896
Come on, just let me see.

06:35.896 --> 06:37.689
ANNA:
Robert!
You ripped it.

06:37.689 --> 06:39.774
I...

06:39.774 --> 06:41.276
Oh, dear.

06:41.276 --> 06:42.986
It's ruined!

06:42.986 --> 06:45.404
I-I really didn't mean to.

06:45.404 --> 06:47.366
It's okay, Anna.

06:47.366 --> 06:49.534
You can draw a new one.

06:51.078 --> 06:53.538
True art
is ever-changing.

06:54.455 --> 06:55.874
A-are you okay?

06:58.585 --> 06:59.961
Good.

07:01.420 --> 07:04.341
[♪♪♪]

07:07.010 --> 07:08.970
I agree, and if
the town doesn't grow,

07:08.970 --> 07:10.471
neither does my business.

07:10.471 --> 07:12.432
I was expecting to pick up
a lot of work.

07:12.432 --> 07:13.892
How could
this happen?

07:13.892 --> 07:15.769
First, Abigail
helps Gowen get parole,

07:15.769 --> 07:18.021
and now the railroad
is walking all over her.

07:18.021 --> 07:19.731
Maybe the job
is too big for her.

07:19.731 --> 07:21.024
Abigail is too ki--

07:21.024 --> 07:22.525
[STAMMERS]

07:24.986 --> 07:26.863
Is there a problem?

07:29.366 --> 07:31.785
They're not happy
about the railroad.

07:33.995 --> 07:35.705
I see.

07:35.705 --> 07:37.498
Well, if it matters,
neither am I,

07:37.498 --> 07:39.042
but we're not giving up.

07:39.042 --> 07:42.337
They're a big company, Abigail,
and we're a small town.

07:42.337 --> 07:44.881
How do we make them
do what they promised?

07:44.881 --> 07:47.050
I don't know,
but we will find a way.

07:47.884 --> 07:49.136
Of course you will.

07:51.512 --> 07:53.390
Thank you.
Certainly.

07:53.390 --> 07:54.975
Florence,
wait up.

07:54.975 --> 07:56.559
[SIGHS]

07:56.559 --> 07:59.313
They're just afraid,
Abigail, that's all.

07:59.313 --> 08:01.898
To be honest,
so am I.

08:01.898 --> 08:03.358
The town will survive

08:03.358 --> 08:05.193
if the railroad
doesn't stop here.

08:05.193 --> 08:07.446
Some merchants might fare
better than others,

08:07.446 --> 08:09.697
yes, but it's not like
we're gonna fade away.

08:09.697 --> 08:12.242
Lee, I have bigger plans
for this town

08:12.242 --> 08:13.952
than just
"not fade away".

08:13.952 --> 08:15.703
Right.

08:17.247 --> 08:19.458
Right.

08:19.458 --> 08:21.709
[ALL CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

08:26.173 --> 08:27.757
Hello, Mrs. Hayford.

08:27.757 --> 08:30.135
Anna, where did you go?
We were looking for you.

08:30.135 --> 08:31.678
She came running home
at lunch.

08:31.678 --> 08:33.180
Why? Did something happen?

08:33.180 --> 08:35.056
Robert ripped
my drawing this morning.

08:35.056 --> 08:37.017
I was working
really hard on it.

08:37.017 --> 08:40.437
Anna, I'm so sorry.
I'll speak with Robert.

08:40.437 --> 08:42.147
Why don't you
go and play?

08:43.690 --> 08:45.859
I don't mean to make a fuss,
Miss Thatcher,

08:45.859 --> 08:47.777
but from what Anna tells me,
your sister

08:47.777 --> 08:49.529
simply brushed
the whole thing off.

08:49.529 --> 08:51.239
That's why
Anna's so upset.

08:51.239 --> 08:53.533
Julie is apprenticing
with me.

08:53.533 --> 08:55.952
She's still learning
how to manage a classroom.

08:55.952 --> 08:57.662
I will have a word with her.

08:57.662 --> 08:59.873
[♪♪♪]

09:09.424 --> 09:11.634
[♪♪♪]

09:23.438 --> 09:25.524
[STARTER SPUTTERING]

09:28.568 --> 09:30.320
[STARTER CONTINUES
SPUTTERING]

09:30.320 --> 09:33.073
You're sure
you can't stay for dinner?

09:33.073 --> 09:35.992
The special tonight's
beef stew at Abigail's Cafe.

09:35.992 --> 09:37.702
You can't pass that up.

09:37.702 --> 09:41.039
Well, thank you, but I have
dinner plans in Rock Creek.

09:41.039 --> 09:42.623
Well, plans can change.

09:43.583 --> 09:45.377
What's that old saying--

09:45.377 --> 09:47.879
"the best-laid plans
of mice and men"?

09:49.630 --> 09:51.841
Car was running fine
when I got here.

09:52.842 --> 09:54.511
Mysterious machines.

09:54.511 --> 09:56.304
I favor a horse, myself.

09:56.304 --> 09:59.391
I don't suppose there's
a mechanic in this town.

09:59.391 --> 10:01.017
No, sadly, there's not.

10:01.017 --> 10:04.271
There's one in Union City,
so if you send a wire,

10:04.271 --> 10:06.773
might be here
in a couple of days.

10:06.773 --> 10:08.149
Why so long?

10:08.149 --> 10:12.362
Well, the stage from Union City
is very slow.

10:12.362 --> 10:14.948
Too bad he couldn't
take the train.

10:16.991 --> 10:19.160
I guess I'd better
get a room.

10:19.160 --> 10:20.537
Well, let me
remind you

10:20.537 --> 10:22.914
about the beef stew
down at Abigail's Cafe.

10:22.914 --> 10:25.666
Compliments
of Hope Valley.

10:25.666 --> 10:27.919
I don't think
I have much choice.

10:29.963 --> 10:32.173
[♪♪♪]

10:52.819 --> 10:54.404
I was walking by.

10:54.404 --> 10:56.906
And you noticed
the dress again?

10:56.906 --> 10:58.699
Is it for
a special occasion?

10:58.699 --> 11:00.743
It's our
anniversary soon.

11:00.743 --> 11:02.162
Kurt is taking me
to a dance

11:02.162 --> 11:04.372
in Benson Hills.

11:04.372 --> 11:06.124
I wanted to buy
a new dress--

11:06.124 --> 11:08.876
Mm-hm?
Something Kurt would like.

11:08.876 --> 11:11.630
Feels like I haven't bought
a nice dress in years.

11:13.840 --> 11:15.049
I'll tell you what.

11:15.049 --> 11:17.010
Why don't you come inside
and try it on?

11:17.010 --> 11:18.428
Oh, I couldn't.

11:18.428 --> 11:21.306
Don't be silly!
Of course you can.

11:21.306 --> 11:23.891
I don't know, Rosemary.
The price...

11:23.891 --> 11:26.227
It doesn't cost
anything to try it on.

11:26.227 --> 11:28.813
Come on.
What's the harm?

11:28.813 --> 11:31.316
There's the spirit!

11:36.863 --> 11:38.990
WESTON:
When we entered
into the agreement,

11:38.990 --> 11:40.367
we thought Hope Valley

11:40.367 --> 11:43.495
had the best growth potential
in the area.

11:43.495 --> 11:45.330
Now we think Jameson does.

11:45.330 --> 11:49.042
Well, then put a depot
in both towns.

11:49.042 --> 11:50.669
Unfortunately,

11:50.669 --> 11:54.255
that's more than the railroad
is willing to invest.

11:54.255 --> 11:56.216
You're a lawyer,
aren't you, Mr. Weston?

11:56.216 --> 11:59.093
Chief counsel
with the National Pacific.

11:59.093 --> 12:01.762
Didn't they teach contract law
where you went to school?

12:01.762 --> 12:05.058
Absolutely, which is why I know
that contracts can be altered,

12:05.058 --> 12:07.477
or even terminated.

12:07.477 --> 12:08.936
Through negotiations, yes,

12:08.936 --> 12:12.148
but that's not what
you're doing, you're dictating.

12:12.148 --> 12:14.401
I'm doing
what's best for my client.

12:14.401 --> 12:16.444
I'm trying to do
what's best for my town.

12:16.444 --> 12:17.862
You're doing a fine job.

12:19.864 --> 12:22.534
It's just not going
to change anything.

12:22.534 --> 12:23.993
[COINS CLINK]

12:26.580 --> 12:28.915
Mr. Weston.

12:28.915 --> 12:31.626
I'd like you to meet
with the town,

12:31.626 --> 12:33.752
explain to them
why this is happening.

12:33.752 --> 12:37.131
I'm sorry, Mayor.
I'm a lawyer,

12:37.131 --> 12:40.051
I'm not a public relations
executive.

12:41.844 --> 12:43.638
Good day.

12:45.306 --> 12:47.934
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

12:49.436 --> 12:52.063
ROSEMARY:
How are you doing in there,
Wilma?

12:52.063 --> 12:53.732
WILMA:
One second.

12:53.732 --> 12:58.152
We're in luck!
It's almost exactly her size.

12:58.152 --> 12:59.987
Look at you!

12:59.987 --> 13:01.573
I could make
a few alterations--

13:01.573 --> 13:03.199
Oh, no,
no, no, no!

13:03.199 --> 13:07.078
The dress is absolutely
stunning on you.

13:07.078 --> 13:08.663
Really?

13:11.958 --> 13:13.418
It's a beautiful dress.

13:15.211 --> 13:17.838
But I don't think
it's a good idea.

13:18.881 --> 13:20.467
Well, since I'm the designer,

13:20.467 --> 13:23.303
I think I should have a say
in who gets to wear my dress.

13:23.303 --> 13:25.346
I can honestly say
I wouldn't want anyone

13:25.346 --> 13:26.973
to wear it except for you.

13:28.182 --> 13:30.602
We don't have a lot of money.

13:30.602 --> 13:34.314
To be honest, I make most
of my family's clothes myself.

13:35.649 --> 13:38.025
Well, what if I gave you
my designer discount?

13:38.025 --> 13:39.110
Forty percent off.

13:40.612 --> 13:42.572
Are you sure?

13:42.572 --> 13:44.365
I'm sure.

13:44.365 --> 13:47.243
I didn't think I could ever
own something like this.

13:47.243 --> 13:48.536
Is that a yes?

13:48.536 --> 13:51.247
Yes!
I hope Kurt likes it.

13:51.247 --> 13:53.040
Oh, I promise you, Wilma,

13:53.040 --> 13:55.918
he won't even remember
his own name

13:55.918 --> 13:57.545
when he sees you
in that dress.

13:58.672 --> 14:01.132
[BELL CLANGING]

14:01.132 --> 14:03.092
ELIZABETH:
Have a great day, everyone!

14:03.092 --> 14:05.094
Be sure to show
your parents

14:05.094 --> 14:06.721
your beautiful artwork!

14:06.721 --> 14:08.473
You did a great job.

14:08.473 --> 14:10.891
ELIZABETH:
Anna, may I see your drawing?

14:12.686 --> 14:16.523
Oh...and the one
that got torn?

14:17.816 --> 14:20.318
Oh, well, I can see
it's very good.

14:21.319 --> 14:22.987
It really was.

14:22.987 --> 14:25.990
I'm really sorry
I wrecked your picture, Anna.

14:25.990 --> 14:27.617
You didn't mean to.

14:27.617 --> 14:29.661
Thank you
for saying that, Robert.

14:32.163 --> 14:34.123
Thanks, Miss Thatcher.

14:36.334 --> 14:38.545
[♪♪♪]

14:39.462 --> 14:40.921
[SIGHS]

14:40.921 --> 14:43.466
Being around young people
may be exhilarating,

14:43.466 --> 14:44.843
but it's exhausting too.

14:44.843 --> 14:47.011
How do you keep this up,
day after day?

14:47.011 --> 14:48.722
Julie,
we need to talk.

14:48.722 --> 14:50.557
About what?

14:50.557 --> 14:52.726
Well, Anna
ran home at lunch

14:52.726 --> 14:54.728
because Robert
tore her drawing.

14:54.728 --> 14:57.689
Really? She didn't seem
that upset about it at the time.

14:57.689 --> 15:00.066
Well, exactly
what happened?

15:00.066 --> 15:01.568
From what
I could gather,

15:01.568 --> 15:03.653
Robert was reaching
to see Anna's drawing,

15:03.653 --> 15:05.196
and he accidentally
ripped it.

15:05.196 --> 15:07.532
But did she seem okay?

15:09.200 --> 15:10.702
I suppose not.

15:12.328 --> 15:14.539
Sometimes, children
are reluctant to speak up

15:14.539 --> 15:16.249
when something's
bothering them.

15:16.249 --> 15:19.001
You have to do a little digging
to find out what's wrong.

15:19.001 --> 15:22.422
When I think I'm getting
the hang of teaching.
Julie,

15:22.422 --> 15:23.757
mistakes are how we learn.

15:23.757 --> 15:25.925
I apologized
to Anna's mother.

15:25.925 --> 15:27.677
Robert apologized to Anna.

15:27.677 --> 15:29.763
We'll move on.

15:34.392 --> 15:35.727
CODY:
You take that back.

15:35.727 --> 15:37.311
Make me.
Take it back!

15:37.311 --> 15:38.354
No!

15:38.354 --> 15:39.313
[BOTH GRUNTING]

15:39.313 --> 15:41.023
Robert! Cody!
Stop that!

15:41.023 --> 15:43.234
Stop it.
Now, what is this all about?

15:43.234 --> 15:45.069
He said my mom
was a bad mayor.

15:45.069 --> 15:47.071
What I said was
my dad thinks

15:47.071 --> 15:48.406
Mr. Coulter should be mayor.

15:48.406 --> 15:49.824
He'll get us
the railroad.

15:49.824 --> 15:51.367
My mom will get us
the railroad.

15:51.367 --> 15:52.786
No, she won't!
Yes, she will!

15:52.786 --> 15:54.454
Boys, listen to me,
both of you.

15:54.454 --> 15:56.038
There is to be no fighting.

15:56.038 --> 15:57.791
But he said--
Doesn't matter what he said!

15:57.791 --> 15:59.208
No fighting, period.

15:59.208 --> 16:00.627
Do you understand?

16:00.627 --> 16:01.711
Yes, Miss Thatcher.

16:01.711 --> 16:03.504
Yes, ma'am.

16:03.504 --> 16:05.965
Now, you two are friends.

16:05.965 --> 16:07.341
It's all right to disagree,

16:07.341 --> 16:08.968
but you can't let
what's happening

16:08.968 --> 16:11.262
with the railroad
affect your friendship.

16:12.680 --> 16:14.682
Why don't you take your seat,
Robert?

16:14.682 --> 16:16.517
Yes, ma'am.

16:18.436 --> 16:19.604
Cody...

16:19.604 --> 16:21.648
I know you want
to defend your mom,

16:21.648 --> 16:23.190
and that's admirable,

16:23.190 --> 16:25.568
but fighting
doesn't solve anything.

16:25.568 --> 16:28.404
It only leads to more anger
and more fighting.

16:28.404 --> 16:30.406
I'm sorry.

16:32.241 --> 16:34.118
Being the mayor is a hard job,

16:34.118 --> 16:36.245
but your mom
knows what she's doing.

16:36.245 --> 16:38.498
Okay?

16:40.875 --> 16:42.752
[EXHALES DEEPLY]

16:47.006 --> 16:49.133
[♪♪♪]

16:49.133 --> 16:52.637
So, are you and Jesse
still on a break?

16:52.637 --> 16:55.431
I just want to be sure
I'm ready to get serious again.

16:55.431 --> 16:57.266
Mm. I understand.

16:58.601 --> 17:00.603
But does Jesse?

17:00.603 --> 17:03.815
He's trying,
but it's hard on him.

17:03.815 --> 17:07.944
Hmm. Men aren't emotionally
sophisticated creatures.

17:07.944 --> 17:10.947
Generally, the best you can
get out of them is a blank nod.

17:10.947 --> 17:13.616
But Lee seems to be
pretty understanding.

17:13.616 --> 17:15.869
Oh, well, emotions
are like a muscle--

17:15.869 --> 17:18.788
takes work to make them strong.
Lee doesn't realize it,

17:18.788 --> 17:21.833
but I have him doing emotional
push-ups at least twice a day.

17:21.833 --> 17:22.959
Well, it's working.

17:22.959 --> 17:24.418
[CHUCKLES]
Fit as a fiddle.

17:29.131 --> 17:30.884
Oh! Mr. and Mrs. Lawson.

17:30.884 --> 17:32.844
What brings you
into the shop today?

17:32.844 --> 17:35.013
Perhaps a new suit
for you, Mr. Lawson?

17:35.013 --> 17:37.348
I understand you have
an anniversary coming up.

17:37.348 --> 17:40.184
Thank you, but we're here
to return a dress.

17:40.184 --> 17:42.645
It's unworn,
I hope it's not a problem.

17:42.645 --> 17:45.105
Was there something
wrong with it?

17:45.105 --> 17:46.190
No, not at all.

17:46.190 --> 17:47.734
She got
a little carried away.

17:47.734 --> 17:49.986
People like us, well,
we don't have the money

17:49.986 --> 17:53.322
for fancy clothes like this.
I understand.

17:53.322 --> 17:55.115
It is a shame.

17:55.115 --> 17:57.368
Wilma does look beautiful
in this dress.

17:57.368 --> 17:59.871
I'm sure she does.

18:01.205 --> 18:03.583
Very well.
I'll get you your refund.

18:03.583 --> 18:05.877
KURT:
We appreciate it.

18:05.877 --> 18:07.169
[REGISTER BELL DINGS]

18:07.169 --> 18:08.337
[BILLS CRINKLE]

18:08.337 --> 18:10.381
Well, there you are.

18:11.758 --> 18:14.301
Thank you.
We should get home now.

18:16.596 --> 18:18.056
Wilma?

18:18.056 --> 18:21.059
I'm really sorry if
I caused you any trouble.

18:21.059 --> 18:23.310
It's just the way
you looked in that dress--

18:23.310 --> 18:24.854
You didn't do
anything wrong.

18:24.854 --> 18:26.689
We just can't
afford it.

18:26.689 --> 18:28.900
[♪♪♪]

18:36.574 --> 18:38.158
JULIE:
Remember--

18:38.158 --> 18:39.577
I want to see a person

18:39.577 --> 18:42.956
nice and prominent
in your landscapes.

18:43.957 --> 18:45.499
Miss Thatcher?

18:45.499 --> 18:47.585
I'm done.
Oh!

18:49.754 --> 18:52.339
Oh, those are so beautiful.

18:54.550 --> 18:56.761
[♪♪♪]

19:01.599 --> 19:04.018
Thank you so much, girls.

19:07.814 --> 19:11.567
Here you are.
A few more for you.

19:19.951 --> 19:22.202
[GASPS QUIETLY]

19:25.081 --> 19:26.540
Julie...

19:26.540 --> 19:28.751
why are you
giving Laura an A?

19:28.751 --> 19:30.837
I don't see a person
in that sketch.

19:30.837 --> 19:33.255
Well, look at how
beautiful her work is.

19:33.255 --> 19:35.967
Yes, but we have to assess them
based on

19:35.967 --> 19:37.551
how well they
follow directions.

19:37.551 --> 19:39.303
Come on! Look at it.

19:39.303 --> 19:42.140
I am...
and I don't see a person.

19:43.933 --> 19:46.393
Laura didn't include a person

19:46.393 --> 19:48.521
because she isn't as confident
drawing them.

19:48.521 --> 19:50.439
We have to guide
and encourage her

19:50.439 --> 19:52.775
to go beyond
her natural abilities.

19:52.775 --> 19:55.903
A letter grade is just
one of the tools of the trade.

19:57.864 --> 19:59.573
You're not
doing Laura any favors

19:59.573 --> 20:01.784
by giving her an A
when she hasn't earned one.

20:01.784 --> 20:04.328
I'm just not getting this.
That's not true!

20:04.328 --> 20:07.414
The children
are learning a lot from you,

20:07.414 --> 20:10.043
and they really like you.
I can tell.

20:11.169 --> 20:12.837
It's just that,
sometimes,

20:12.837 --> 20:14.714
we have to do
the difficult thing

20:14.714 --> 20:16.841
for their own good.

20:18.759 --> 20:20.511
JULIE:
This is hard.

20:20.511 --> 20:23.806
Yes...
it can be.

20:26.517 --> 20:28.728
[♪♪♪]

20:31.939 --> 20:34.108
ABIGAIL:
This whole mess
with the railroad

20:34.108 --> 20:35.317
is getting out of hand.

20:35.317 --> 20:37.070
The boys will be
fine, Abigail.

20:37.070 --> 20:38.612
It's just
a part of growing up.

20:38.612 --> 20:41.115
I still feel responsible
for them fighting.

20:41.115 --> 20:42.950
You? How are you responsible?

20:42.950 --> 20:44.702
After what happened
with Ray Wyatt,

20:44.702 --> 20:47.287
I should've been prepared
to take on the railroad.

20:47.287 --> 20:49.373
Abigail,
you have a contract.

20:49.373 --> 20:51.500
No one can blame you
for relying on that.

20:51.500 --> 20:52.752
I guess not.

20:52.752 --> 20:54.336
Look, you will
find a way

20:54.336 --> 20:56.214
to beat the railroad,
I know you will.

20:56.214 --> 20:58.465
You're the best mayor
Hope Valley has ever had.

20:58.465 --> 21:00.760
You have to say that.
You're my best friend.

21:00.760 --> 21:03.221
And you should know by now
that your best friend

21:03.221 --> 21:05.264
would never lie to you.

21:05.264 --> 21:07.474
[♪♪♪]

21:12.230 --> 21:15.149
ROSEMARY:
I just feel awful about Wilma.

21:15.149 --> 21:17.317
She loved that dress.
And why wouldn't she?

21:17.317 --> 21:18.861
She looked gorgeous in it.

21:18.861 --> 21:20.821
I want her
to have that dress!

21:20.821 --> 21:23.282
Sweetheart, this is about
more than just money.

21:23.282 --> 21:24.533
This is about pride.

21:24.533 --> 21:26.535
People like
Kurt and Wilma,

21:26.535 --> 21:28.121
they want to make
their own way.

21:28.121 --> 21:30.164
They don't
want to take charity.

21:30.164 --> 21:32.583
Still I wish there
was something I could do.

21:32.583 --> 21:34.961
She said she hasn't had
a new dress in years.

21:34.961 --> 21:38.422
And do you know, everything she
wears, she makes herself?

21:38.422 --> 21:39.882
[GASPS QUIETLY]

21:39.882 --> 21:41.092
Uh-oh.

21:41.092 --> 21:42.384
I know that look.

21:42.384 --> 21:44.971
If Wilma makes clothes
for her entire family,

21:44.971 --> 21:46.847
she must be
an excellent seamstress.

21:46.847 --> 21:49.642
[GASPS]
She could make
the very same dress!

21:49.642 --> 21:52.228
And how
can she do that?

21:52.228 --> 21:54.105
I'm going to give her
the pattern.

21:54.105 --> 21:56.190
Well, is Dottie gonna
be okay with that?

21:56.190 --> 21:58.317
Doesn't it hurt
her business?

21:58.317 --> 22:01.279
Well, yes...but--
You don't understand.

22:01.279 --> 22:04.448
Sometimes, when you see someone
in a piece you have designed,

22:04.448 --> 22:07.034
you just know
it was meant for them.

22:07.034 --> 22:09.453
So this dress was
just meant for Wilma?

22:09.453 --> 22:10.454
Yes!

22:10.454 --> 22:12.206
And if I get her
the pattern,

22:12.206 --> 22:13.874
she might just
finish in time.

22:13.874 --> 22:15.459
In time for what?

22:15.459 --> 22:17.295
To finish it
before her anniversary.

22:17.295 --> 22:20.047
I want her night
to be special.

22:20.047 --> 22:21.381
She deserves it.

22:23.676 --> 22:26.179
Well, if she deserves it.

22:26.179 --> 22:27.763
[CHUCKLES]

22:32.810 --> 22:35.062
Cody, you should be in bed
by now, young man.

22:35.062 --> 22:37.190
I was just finishing
my prayers.

22:37.190 --> 22:39.733
Well, that's a good reason.

22:42.360 --> 22:43.904
Miss Thatcher
told me about

22:43.904 --> 22:45.990
what happened
in school today.

22:45.990 --> 22:47.950
I'm sorry, Mom.

22:48.868 --> 22:50.744
I'm sorry too, Cody.

22:50.744 --> 22:53.039
For what?
Putting you and Robert

22:53.039 --> 22:54.248
in the middle of this.

22:54.248 --> 22:56.209
You're just kids.
You're too young

22:56.209 --> 22:58.418
to worry about
things like the railroad.

22:58.418 --> 23:01.088
I didn't want
to fight with him,

23:01.088 --> 23:02.589
but he was being mean to you.

23:02.589 --> 23:05.009
And I appreciate
you wanting to stick up for me,

23:05.009 --> 23:06.635
but we talked about this.

23:06.635 --> 23:08.012
I want you to use your words

23:08.012 --> 23:10.848
to solve a disagreement,
not your fists.

23:10.848 --> 23:12.725
I know.

23:12.725 --> 23:14.227
You're not mad at me,
are you?

23:14.227 --> 23:16.270
Never.

23:20.816 --> 23:22.776
Mom?
Hm?

23:22.776 --> 23:25.363
I like being on your side.

23:26.613 --> 23:29.200
I love you, Cody.

23:29.200 --> 23:31.327
Get some sleep.

23:32.452 --> 23:34.663
[♪♪♪]

23:45.716 --> 23:49.220
Wilma! Wilma!
I'm glad I found you.

23:49.220 --> 23:51.222
Could I talk with you
for a moment?

23:51.222 --> 23:53.724
Of course.
If this is about the dress,

23:53.724 --> 23:55.559
I am very sorry
about what happened.

23:55.559 --> 23:58.562
Don't be silly. I shouldn't
have pushed you into buying it.

23:58.562 --> 24:01.523
It's not your fault.
Your dress was lovely.

24:01.523 --> 24:02.816
But I have to accept

24:02.816 --> 24:05.027
that a nice dress
isn't in the cards for me.

24:05.027 --> 24:06.320
Well, what if I told you

24:06.320 --> 24:08.281
there was a way
you could have that dress

24:08.281 --> 24:10.908
without paying
so much money for it?

24:10.908 --> 24:12.868
These are the patterns
for that dress.

24:12.868 --> 24:15.871
You're a good seamstress. This
is nothing you can't handle.

24:15.871 --> 24:17.290
All you need is fabric.

24:17.290 --> 24:19.125
This is so kind of you.

24:19.125 --> 24:20.918
Are you sure
this is okay?

24:20.918 --> 24:23.545
It'll be
on one condition.

24:23.545 --> 24:24.964
What's that?

24:24.964 --> 24:27.716
You finish it
in time for your anniversary.

24:27.716 --> 24:29.509
Then I'd better hurry!

24:29.509 --> 24:30.844
[BOTH LAUGHING]

24:32.346 --> 24:34.514
[♪♪♪]

24:34.514 --> 24:36.767
[SIGHS]

24:36.767 --> 24:38.811
Feel free to stop in again.

24:41.730 --> 24:43.941
[♪♪♪]

24:45.943 --> 24:49.238
Rosemary, I just sold
one of your designs

24:49.238 --> 24:50.948
from the traveling collection.

24:51.991 --> 24:53.826
That's wonderful.

24:54.785 --> 24:56.536
You don't sound enthusiastic.

24:58.164 --> 25:00.498
We're partners, aren't we?

25:00.498 --> 25:02.876
Well...yes.

25:02.876 --> 25:05.921
So in the spirit
of partnership,

25:05.921 --> 25:07.798
I wanted to tell you

25:07.798 --> 25:11.344
that I may have given away
one of our patterns...

25:11.344 --> 25:13.971
to Wilma Lawson.

25:13.971 --> 25:16.015
For free.

25:16.015 --> 25:17.057
Uh, just now.

25:17.057 --> 25:20.602
You may have,
or you did?

25:20.602 --> 25:23.521
She fell in love with
one of our new evening gowns

25:23.521 --> 25:26.524
and she tried it on. She looked
absolutely beautiful in it.

25:26.524 --> 25:28.735
The day after she bought it,
she returned it.

25:28.735 --> 25:31.030
Her husband said
they couldn't afford it.

25:31.030 --> 25:32.698
So you gave her the pattern

25:32.698 --> 25:34.532
so she could
make the dress herself?

25:34.532 --> 25:37.161
Yes. I know, I should've talked
to you about it first.

25:37.161 --> 25:38.620
It was silly of me.
Rosemary.

25:38.620 --> 25:40.831
But you should've seen
the look on her face!

25:40.831 --> 25:42.208
It's their anniversary.

25:42.208 --> 25:43.417
Rosemary?
All she wanted

25:43.417 --> 25:44.793
was catch
her husband's eye.

25:44.793 --> 25:46.795
She needed to have
something new to wear.

25:46.795 --> 25:48.506
If you want
to dock it from my pay,

25:48.506 --> 25:50.548
I absolutely understand.
Rosemary!

25:50.548 --> 25:52.426
It's fine.

25:52.426 --> 25:53.927
It is?

25:53.927 --> 25:56.430
In fact, you're brilliant.
I am?

25:56.430 --> 25:59.225
This is a completely new
market for us.

25:59.225 --> 26:00.976
Why didn't I think of this
sooner?

26:00.976 --> 26:04.397
Designer fashion
at bargain prices.

26:04.397 --> 26:07.983
Y-yes...?
We can call it...

26:07.983 --> 26:09.985
"sew your own."

26:09.985 --> 26:11.445
We provide the pattern,

26:11.445 --> 26:13.280
the customer buys the fabric.

26:13.280 --> 26:15.699
Oh, this is a can't-miss,
Rosemary. Oh!

26:15.699 --> 26:18.952
Just exactly
what I had...planned!

26:18.952 --> 26:20.787
Oh!

26:25.167 --> 26:26.626
Here you go.

26:26.626 --> 26:28.128
Thanks,
Miss Thatcher.

26:28.128 --> 26:29.713
I got an A!

26:29.713 --> 26:31.131
I only got
a B-minus?

26:31.131 --> 26:33.008
[♪♪♪]

26:33.008 --> 26:35.511
But Hattie
got an A.

26:35.511 --> 26:37.888
I'm afraid
you didn't follow directions.

26:37.888 --> 26:39.181
I specifically said

26:39.181 --> 26:41.475
there had to be a person
in your landscape.

26:41.475 --> 26:43.143
But a B-minus?

26:43.143 --> 26:45.062
I had to mark you down
for that,

26:45.062 --> 26:48.648
but the rest is beautiful.

26:48.648 --> 26:51.693
You have the talent
to draw a person, Laura.

26:51.693 --> 26:53.571
Just try.

26:53.571 --> 26:55.948
It takes practice.

26:57.116 --> 26:59.243
Yes, Miss Thatcher.

27:00.077 --> 27:03.080
[♪♪♪]

27:11.880 --> 27:13.715
I feel so mean.

27:13.715 --> 27:15.551
Oh, you're not mean.

27:15.551 --> 27:18.387
You're just
being a teacher.

27:20.764 --> 27:24.226
ELIZABETH:
So, you are still
having a town meeting,

27:24.226 --> 27:26.895
though the man from the railroad
said he's not going?

27:26.895 --> 27:29.398
Bill promises to get him there.
And if he shows up,

27:29.398 --> 27:31.150
all we can do
is state our case.

27:31.150 --> 27:32.650
I have faith.

27:32.650 --> 27:35.279
[CHUCKLES]
I wish everyone
was as optimistic as you.

27:35.279 --> 27:37.531
Cody tells me
that the children

27:37.531 --> 27:39.241
have been talking
about the meeting.

27:39.241 --> 27:41.034
They've been asking
me about it too.

27:41.034 --> 27:43.787
I think they're scared
about what it means for the town

27:43.787 --> 27:45.080
and their families.

27:45.080 --> 27:47.665
I've tried
to put their minds at ease.

27:47.665 --> 27:49.835
I hate to think about
them sitting at home,

27:49.835 --> 27:51.378
worrying about it.

27:51.378 --> 27:53.297
Maybe I could
spend some time

27:53.297 --> 27:55.215
with them tonight,
during the meeting.

27:55.215 --> 27:57.801
We could do an activity,
take their minds off things?

27:57.801 --> 27:59.345
We couldn't ask you
to do that.

27:59.345 --> 28:01.096
You should be
at the meeting too.

28:01.096 --> 28:03.056
I want to be
with my students.

28:03.056 --> 28:05.851
Okay. Why don't you
do it at the café?

28:05.851 --> 28:07.144
I'll bake some cookies.

28:07.144 --> 28:08.145
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

28:08.145 --> 28:10.356
[♪♪♪]

28:13.359 --> 28:15.444
[ENGINE PURRS]

28:18.905 --> 28:20.240
What's this?

28:20.240 --> 28:22.909
A citation. Your car's
illegally parked.

28:22.909 --> 28:25.454
What?
No, it's
a town ordinance.

28:25.454 --> 28:28.123
No parking your car on city
streets more than 24 hours.

28:28.123 --> 28:30.250
This is ridiculous!
You know as well as I do

28:30.250 --> 28:34.296
this car wasn't running. In
fact, I think you sabotaged it.

28:34.296 --> 28:36.590
Well, there'll be a judge
in town in a few days

28:36.590 --> 28:38.634
to hear
this outrageous accusation.

28:38.634 --> 28:42.095
I'll just pay the fine
and go.

28:42.095 --> 28:43.556
You bribing me?

28:43.556 --> 28:46.350
No, I said
I would pay the fine.

28:46.350 --> 28:48.894
Sounded like a bribe.

28:48.894 --> 28:50.396
What is it you want?

28:50.396 --> 28:52.898
I'd like a little justice
in the world, Mr. Weston.

28:52.898 --> 28:54.692
Seems like
we're in short supply.

28:56.569 --> 28:59.321
Do you think that if I go
to this town hall meeting,

28:59.321 --> 29:01.407
that bad things
will stop happening to me?

29:01.407 --> 29:03.783
I've been known
to be a betting man.

29:03.783 --> 29:06.704
My wager would be...yes.

29:11.791 --> 29:14.002
[♪♪♪]

29:21.927 --> 29:23.762
Good evening, Mr. Lawson!

29:23.762 --> 29:24.971
Evening.

29:24.971 --> 29:26.557
You haven't seen
my wife around?

29:26.557 --> 29:28.517
She left a note,
wanting me to meet her.

29:28.517 --> 29:30.102
I just spoke with her.

29:30.102 --> 29:32.812
She wanted me to tell you
she'd be along any minute.

29:32.812 --> 29:34.189
Oh. All right.

29:34.189 --> 29:35.733
I heard you two are celebrating

29:35.733 --> 29:38.402
your anniversary this evening.
How many years?

29:38.402 --> 29:40.613
Ten years.
Oh! Congratulations

29:40.613 --> 29:42.948
I'm sure they've been
very happy.
They have.

29:42.948 --> 29:44.575
Uh, where exactly
is Wilma?

29:44.575 --> 29:46.619
We have to be getting
to Benson Hills soon.

29:46.619 --> 29:49.996
She's just making a few
adjustments in the dress shop.

29:49.996 --> 29:51.665
Adjustments? To what?

29:51.665 --> 29:54.501
Well...
take a look for yourself.

29:56.629 --> 29:58.380
[EXHALES]

30:00.549 --> 30:02.884
[♪♪♪]

30:05.387 --> 30:07.681
What do you think?

30:07.681 --> 30:09.433
Wilma, we talked about this.

30:09.433 --> 30:11.101
It's not the same dress.

30:11.101 --> 30:12.645
I made this myself,

30:12.645 --> 30:14.688
with Rosemary's help.

30:14.688 --> 30:16.774
Don't you like it?

30:16.774 --> 30:19.735
Oh, honey, it's not about
whether or not I like it.

30:19.735 --> 30:21.320
The way you looked at me
just now,

30:21.320 --> 30:24.823
when I walked over here...
I miss that.

30:28.285 --> 30:30.537
You don't need a dress
to be beautiful...

30:31.580 --> 30:32.831
but I gotta say...

30:32.831 --> 30:35.501
this one
is really nice.

30:35.501 --> 30:37.419
And you look
handsome as ever.

30:37.419 --> 30:38.587
We'd better get going,

30:38.587 --> 30:40.422
if we want to make it
to Benson Hills.

30:40.422 --> 30:42.090
You don't
have to worry.

30:42.090 --> 30:44.510
Your ride...approaches.

30:44.510 --> 30:45.594
Our ride?

30:45.594 --> 30:46.679
[ENGINE CHUGGING]

30:46.679 --> 30:48.888
[WILMA GASPS]

30:48.888 --> 30:51.850
It's a special night.

30:51.850 --> 30:53.935
We wanted you
to ride in style.

30:53.935 --> 30:55.395
Oh!

30:55.395 --> 30:57.606
[♪♪♪]

31:00.317 --> 31:02.444
Come on in.

31:04.070 --> 31:06.406
Okay, here we go.

31:06.406 --> 31:07.658
Don't worry.

31:07.658 --> 31:09.909
He drives for me
at the mill all the time,

31:09.909 --> 31:12.037
and I'm sure
he'll be very careful.

31:13.038 --> 31:14.707
Won't you?

31:14.707 --> 31:16.291
Of course!
Right.

31:20.337 --> 31:22.297
[LAUGHING]
Happy Anniversary!

31:22.297 --> 31:24.299
Be careful with my car!

31:24.299 --> 31:26.426
[BOTH LAUGHING]

31:28.470 --> 31:30.055
And we are all
going to suffer

31:30.055 --> 31:32.516
if you don't build that depot
like you promised.

31:32.516 --> 31:34.768
Thank you, Ned.

31:34.768 --> 31:36.687
I'm relying on it.

31:36.687 --> 31:39.439
I just moved my dress shop
into a larger space.

31:41.608 --> 31:44.444
Look, we're all worried
about our economic interests.

31:44.444 --> 31:46.780
Unfortunately,
the railroad's interests

31:46.780 --> 31:49.449
dictate building
the depot in Jameson.

31:49.449 --> 31:51.869
[CROWD MURMURING]

31:53.620 --> 31:56.206
ELIZABETH:
Would anyone
like to hear another story?

31:56.206 --> 31:57.957
KIDS [GRUMBLING]:
No.

31:57.957 --> 32:00.836
How long do you think the
meeting will be, Miss Thatcher?

32:00.836 --> 32:03.589
I don't know...
but what I do know,

32:03.589 --> 32:05.048
is that none
of your parents

32:05.048 --> 32:07.467
would want you
to worry about anything.

32:07.467 --> 32:08.719
But my dad is worried!

32:08.719 --> 32:09.969
[ALL AGREEING]

32:09.969 --> 32:11.680
My parents don't want
to leave.

32:11.680 --> 32:13.056
Mine either!

32:13.056 --> 32:15.058
Why isn't the railroad
building a depot?

32:15.058 --> 32:16.101
Yeah!

32:16.101 --> 32:17.770
Didn't they
make a promise?

32:17.770 --> 32:20.564
They signed a contract,
which is like giving their word.

32:20.564 --> 32:22.148
Then why won't they build it?

32:22.148 --> 32:24.150
GIRL: Yeah!
I wish we could see

32:24.150 --> 32:25.778
what's going on
in that meeting.

32:25.778 --> 32:26.779
Me too.

32:26.779 --> 32:28.071
Could we,
Miss Thatcher?

32:28.071 --> 32:29.823
Could we?
ALL: Yeah!

32:31.366 --> 32:33.159
You know...

32:33.159 --> 32:36.371
it's time we showed Mr. Weston
just how much this means to us.

32:36.371 --> 32:37.915
Follow me.

32:37.915 --> 32:40.166
[ALL CHEERING]

32:41.167 --> 32:42.795
I agreed to attend
this meeting,

32:42.795 --> 32:44.379
but it's getting late.

32:48.091 --> 32:52.095
Unless someone has
something new to add...?

32:53.513 --> 32:54.556
I do.

32:57.768 --> 32:59.352
As a businessman,

32:59.352 --> 33:03.440
I, uh, cannot fault you
for valuing profits,

33:03.440 --> 33:06.234
but you need know
that this decision

33:06.234 --> 33:08.862
will affect
your bottom line.

33:08.862 --> 33:11.448
If the railroad
reneges on its promise

33:11.448 --> 33:13.617
to build a depot here
in Hope Valley,

33:13.617 --> 33:16.202
the sawmill will no longer
use the railroad

33:16.202 --> 33:17.621
to transport its lumber.

33:17.621 --> 33:19.957
WESTON [SCOFFING]:
Don't be ridiculous.

33:19.957 --> 33:21.875
How will you get
your lumber to market?

33:21.875 --> 33:24.043
The old-fashioned way.
Horse and wagon.

33:25.504 --> 33:27.464
Your costs will go
through the roof.

33:27.464 --> 33:29.466
Mm-hmm. The money
you've already laid out

33:29.466 --> 33:31.217
to build a spur line
to my sawmill

33:31.217 --> 33:33.762
that's out the window too.

33:33.762 --> 33:34.847
But you're right.

33:34.847 --> 33:37.516
I will make less money.

33:37.516 --> 33:39.852
But there are things
in this world

33:39.852 --> 33:41.937
that are more important
than money.

33:43.689 --> 33:45.398
Like doing the right thing.

33:48.151 --> 33:51.112
[ALL APPLAUDING]

33:51.112 --> 33:52.990
Okay, okay.

33:59.371 --> 34:00.455
I love you.

34:00.455 --> 34:02.040
Mr. Coulter...

34:02.040 --> 34:03.834
I don't have a choice,

34:03.834 --> 34:06.378
so if you want to run
your sawmill into the ground,

34:06.378 --> 34:07.587
that's your business.

34:08.505 --> 34:10.215
[DOOR OPENING]

34:10.215 --> 34:12.968
Unless there's anything else...

34:14.469 --> 34:16.680
[♪♪♪]

34:21.643 --> 34:23.353
I have something
I'd like to say.

34:23.353 --> 34:26.147
Now, before you close
the railroad office

34:26.147 --> 34:27.315
and leave us for good,

34:27.315 --> 34:28.942
I thought
you should have a look

34:28.942 --> 34:31.987
at the faces of those
most affected by your decision.

34:36.575 --> 34:40.245
ELIZABETH [FORCEFULLY]:
Look at them... Please.

34:45.291 --> 34:49.963
Now, these children are not
numbers on a financial sheet.

34:49.963 --> 34:51.924
They are the future
of Hope Valley,

34:51.924 --> 34:53.466
and this is their home.

34:53.466 --> 34:56.219
And the consequences
of your actions will live on

34:56.219 --> 34:58.764
long after you've driven away,
counting your money.

34:58.764 --> 35:02.267
So, if you are determined
to break your promise,

35:02.267 --> 35:03.685
the very least you can do

35:03.685 --> 35:05.478
is look these children
in the eyes

35:05.478 --> 35:07.564
and explain to them why.

35:09.566 --> 35:11.568
CODY:
I'd like to say something too.

35:11.568 --> 35:14.029
[♪♪♪]

35:14.029 --> 35:15.530
Cody...

35:15.530 --> 35:18.408
Yes, of course,
go right ahead.

35:24.623 --> 35:26.207
My mom told me

35:26.207 --> 35:28.877
I should solve things
with my words and not my fists,

35:28.877 --> 35:30.503
so that's what I want to do.

35:31.880 --> 35:34.466
My name is Cody Stanton.

35:34.466 --> 35:35.926
It used to be Cody Hastings,

35:35.926 --> 35:37.343
but then my parents died

35:37.343 --> 35:39.345
and my sister and I
were orphans.

35:39.345 --> 35:42.099
Miss Abigail adopted us.

35:42.099 --> 35:43.850
She didn't have to,
but she did.

35:43.850 --> 35:46.853
She made a promise to us,

35:46.853 --> 35:48.897
that she would love us,
and raise us,

35:48.897 --> 35:50.857
and teach us
right from wrong.

35:50.857 --> 35:53.652
And she's done that,
every day.

35:53.652 --> 35:55.862
Miss Thatcher is my teacher.

35:55.862 --> 35:58.323
And she's taught me
that my word means everything,

35:58.323 --> 36:00.951
that it's more important
than money or being popular,

36:00.951 --> 36:03.703
so I try not to make
any promises I can't keep.

36:03.703 --> 36:05.288
And, well,

36:05.288 --> 36:07.916
I know the railroad
isn't a man, but you are.

36:07.916 --> 36:11.044
And it seems to me
that if a promise is made,

36:11.044 --> 36:12.504
it should be kept,

36:12.504 --> 36:14.881
so I think the railroad
should keep their promise,

36:14.881 --> 36:17.258
like everyone else
is supposed to do.

36:17.258 --> 36:19.344
[APPLAUDING]

36:21.304 --> 36:24.307
[♪♪♪]

36:40.866 --> 36:42.617
ELIZABETH:
All right, everyone,

36:42.617 --> 36:45.078
we have a busy day today,
so let's get started.

36:45.078 --> 36:47.497
Would you all please
open up your readers?

36:47.497 --> 36:50.167
Could I say a few words,
Miss Thatcher?

36:50.167 --> 36:52.627
Of course,
Miss Thatcher.

36:52.627 --> 36:54.420
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]

36:54.420 --> 36:56.173
First of all,

36:56.173 --> 36:57.549
I want to thank you

36:57.549 --> 36:59.384
for welcoming me
into your classroom.

36:59.384 --> 37:03.138
I have learned so many things
in my time here.

37:03.138 --> 37:04.681
Well, I learned that teaching

37:04.681 --> 37:07.433
is one of
the most challenging...

37:07.433 --> 37:11.479
and rewarding
professions there is.

37:11.479 --> 37:14.357
It requires
so many different skills.

37:14.357 --> 37:16.068
It's a calling.

37:16.068 --> 37:17.861
And it's not for everyone.

37:17.861 --> 37:19.112
[INHALES DEEPLY]

37:19.112 --> 37:20.488
With that in mind,

37:20.488 --> 37:23.449
I'm announcing that,
after today,

37:23.449 --> 37:25.994
I will no longer be
your apprentice teacher.

37:25.994 --> 37:27.787
[ALL GROAN]

37:27.787 --> 37:32.709
Instead...I will be pursuing
my true destiny,

37:32.709 --> 37:34.627
which is to be an artist.

37:34.627 --> 37:36.963
ALL:
Oh...

37:36.963 --> 37:39.091
Are you sure
this is what you want?

37:39.091 --> 37:41.384
I'm sure.

37:41.384 --> 37:44.179
Well, we'll miss you,
won't we, class?

37:44.179 --> 37:46.514
ALL:
Yeah!

37:46.514 --> 37:48.558
Oh! I'll miss you too.

37:49.893 --> 37:51.603
Why don't you all
continue reading

37:51.603 --> 37:53.980
where we left off
yesterday, all right?

37:58.235 --> 38:00.112
Julie...

38:00.112 --> 38:01.947
how did you make
this decision?

38:01.947 --> 38:03.823
Teaching art
in your classroom

38:03.823 --> 38:05.450
made me realize
something--

38:05.450 --> 38:07.953
that the thing that I most
want to do with my life

38:07.953 --> 38:09.996
has been under
my nose all along.

38:09.996 --> 38:11.539
Well, I'm so happy for you.

38:11.539 --> 38:14.251
But I want you
to know something--

38:14.251 --> 38:18.255
I think you could have been
an excellent teacher.

38:18.255 --> 38:21.258
You're the teacher
in the family, Elizabeth.

38:21.258 --> 38:22.508
I need to find out

38:22.508 --> 38:24.677
if I have what it takes
to be the artist.

38:24.677 --> 38:27.430
I'm willing to bet you do.

38:27.430 --> 38:29.557
[CHUCKLES]

38:29.557 --> 38:32.018
[DOOR OPENS]

38:32.018 --> 38:34.271
Sorry she's late.

38:36.189 --> 38:37.607
It's no problem.

38:37.607 --> 38:39.734
Laura, why don't you
take your seat?

38:39.734 --> 38:43.238
Laura was up late,
working on a drawing of me.

38:43.238 --> 38:44.781
Oh!

38:44.781 --> 38:46.116
She's really quite good.

38:46.116 --> 38:48.952
Yeah, she is.

38:48.952 --> 38:50.996
[♪♪♪]

38:52.164 --> 38:54.332
Sorry. Um...

38:54.332 --> 38:57.252
could I just
look at that, please?

38:58.044 --> 38:59.212
Oh. Sure.

38:59.212 --> 39:01.131
Thank you. Thanks.

39:16.562 --> 39:19.024
[WAGONS RUMBLING]

39:19.024 --> 39:21.151
[HORSE WHINNIES]

39:26.990 --> 39:28.700
Lee! What's going on?

39:28.700 --> 39:30.285
Just got word
this morning--

39:30.285 --> 39:33.038
the railroad needs wood
to start building the new depot!

39:33.038 --> 39:34.998
Oh! We did it!

39:34.998 --> 39:36.666
We did it!

39:36.666 --> 39:38.793
[LAUGHING GIDDILY]

39:38.793 --> 39:41.004
[♪♪♪]

39:48.011 --> 39:49.804
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

39:49.804 --> 39:51.973
Just hang on a second.

39:51.973 --> 39:54.517
Mr. Weston,
you changed your mind?

39:54.517 --> 39:59.105
Actually, your whole town
changed it for me.

39:59.105 --> 40:00.690
We're a strong
community.

40:00.690 --> 40:02.150
That you are.

40:02.150 --> 40:05.070
And you should be
very proud of your son.

40:05.070 --> 40:06.905
I am.

40:06.905 --> 40:09.241
You know, he and I
have something in common.

40:10.242 --> 40:12.202
I was an orphan too.

40:12.202 --> 40:17.040
And when he talked about
how you kept your word to him,

40:17.040 --> 40:19.959
to adopt him, to...

40:19.959 --> 40:22.087
raise him right,

40:22.087 --> 40:24.964
it really got me thinking
about my own life.

40:24.964 --> 40:26.591
I wasn't as lucky as him.

40:26.591 --> 40:29.761
Well, you seem to have done
pretty well for yourself.

40:31.054 --> 40:32.889
Our childhood never leaves us.

40:32.889 --> 40:34.391
That's why it's nice

40:34.391 --> 40:37.560
to have a loving hand
to help show you the way.

40:39.187 --> 40:41.606
I wired National Pacific,

40:41.606 --> 40:44.817
and I got them to agree
to honor the contract.

40:44.817 --> 40:46.527
We're going to build
a depot here

40:46.527 --> 40:49.406
and in Jameson.

40:49.406 --> 40:50.865
Thank you.

40:50.865 --> 40:52.825
I'm sure your investment
will pay off.

40:54.411 --> 40:57.163
You're a great Mayor,
Mrs. Stanton...

40:57.163 --> 40:58.748
and an even better parent.

41:01.167 --> 41:02.961
[♪♪♪]

41:02.961 --> 41:05.588
Come on, guys.

41:05.588 --> 41:06.965
Elizabeth! What's wrong?

41:06.965 --> 41:08.425
The battle's coming to a head

41:08.425 --> 41:09.801
in the Northern Territories.

41:09.801 --> 41:11.386
There's a fierce fight
going on,

41:11.386 --> 41:14.806
and the Mounties have
had a lot of casualties.

41:14.806 --> 41:16.266
Oh, Elizabeth.

41:16.266 --> 41:17.350
[SOBBING SOFTLY]

41:17.350 --> 41:19.560
It's going to be okay.

41:19.560 --> 41:21.687
I hope so.

41:23.648 --> 41:25.858
[♪♪♪]

41:30.780 --> 41:32.991
[♪♪♪]
